  <%# ─── Quick start ─── %>

  <section class="prose-section" id="quick-start">
    <h2>Quick start</h2>
    <p>You need a git repo with a Dockerfile, Docker running locally, and SSH access to a Linux VM.</p>

    <h3>1. Install the CLI</h3>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> <%= @cli_install_command %></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>This installs the <code>devopsellence</code> binary to <code>~/.local/bin</code> by default and prints the shell command to add that directory to your <code>PATH</code> when needed. devopsellence is agent-first; the installer also prints the agent skill command, and accepts <code>--install-agent-skill</code> when you want the CLI and skill installed together. Run <code>devopsellence doctor</code> to verify your setup.</p>

    <h3>2. Choose a workspace mode</h3>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> cd my-app</div>
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence mode use solo</div>
        <div class="tl tl-muted"># Use `shared` instead when you want sign-in, org/project/env context, and team workflows.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>Mode is saved per workspace. You can switch later with <code>devopsellence mode use shared</code> or override a single command with <code>--mode</code>.</p>

    <h3>3. Set up the workspace</h3>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence setup</div>
        <div class="tl tl-muted"># solo: initialize config if needed, register or create a node, attach it, and install the agent.</div>
        <div class="tl tl-muted"># shared: sign in, create or select org/project/env, and write workspace config.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>The root verbs stay the same across modes. The selected mode decides whether the CLI runs the solo SSH workflow or the shared control-plane workflow.</p>

    <h3>4. Deploy and inspect</h3>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence deploy</div>
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence status</div>
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence context show</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>In solo mode, the CLI builds locally, transfers the image to each node, writes desired state on disk, and lets the agent reconcile. In shared mode, it builds, pushes, publishes a release, and waits for assigned nodes to converge.</p>

    <h3>5. Switch modes when the workflow changes</h3>
    <p>Start with <code>solo</code> when you want the shortest path to your own VM. Switch to <code>shared</code> when you want browser auth, hosted workflows, managed nodes, or a self-hosted management layer. The public managed path starts at <a href="https://www.devopsellence.com">www.devopsellence.com</a>; the self-hosted shared path lives in <code>control-plane/</code> in this repo.</p>
  </section>

  <%# ─── Connect your servers ─── %>

  <section class="prose-section" id="connect-servers">
    <h2>Shared nodes <span class="mode-badge mode-badge--shared">shared</span></h2>
    <p>In shared mode, nodes are Linux servers or VMs running the devopsellence agent and attached to an organization. Manual node management is available in paid orgs; preview accounts start on managed capacity. Use <code>devopsellence node create</code> to provision a Hetzner node and register it, or <code>devopsellence node register</code> when the server already exists.</p>

    <h3>Provider create: auto-attach to the current environment</h3>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence provider login hetzner</div>
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence node create prod-1 --provider hetzner</div>
        <div class="tl tl-muted"># Server is created, the agent is installed, and the node is registered.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>In shared mode, create uses the same provider flags as solo mode, then runs the registration install command on the new server.</p>

    <h3>Existing server: auto-attach to the current environment</h3>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence node register</div>
        <div class="tl tl-muted"># Node is registered and attached to the current environment.</div>
        <div class="tl tl-muted"># Run the output command on your server to install the agent.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>By default, register generates a token scoped to your current environment. The node starts receiving deployments immediately after the agent is installed.</p>

    <h3>Unassigned: register at org level</h3>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence node register --unassigned</div>
        <div class="tl tl-muted"># Node is registered at the org level, not assigned to any environment.</div>
        <div class="tl tl-muted"># Attach it later with: devopsellence node attach</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>Use <code>--unassigned</code> to register nodes in advance without tying them to an environment. This is useful when you want to provision servers first and assign them later.</p>

    <h3>Attach, detach, label, and diagnose</h3>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence node list</div>
        <div class="tl tl-muted"># Shows all nodes with their ID, status, and assignment.</div>
        <div class="tl">&nbsp;</div>
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence node attach 42 --env production</div>
        <div class="tl tl-muted"># Attaches an unassigned node to an environment.</div>
        <div class="tl">&nbsp;</div>
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence node detach 42</div>
        <div class="tl tl-muted"># Removes the node from its current environment.</div>
        <div class="tl">&nbsp;</div>
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence node label set 42 --labels web,worker</div>
        <div class="tl tl-muted"># Labels control which services run on which nodes.</div>
        <div class="tl">&nbsp;</div>
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence node label set 42 --labels web</div>
        <div class="tl tl-muted"># Run it again with the full label set you want to keep.</div>
        <div class="tl">&nbsp;</div>
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence node diagnose 42</div>
        <div class="tl tl-muted"># Shows node health, agent status, and connectivity.</div>
        <div class="tl">&nbsp;</div>
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence node remove 42</div>
        <div class="tl tl-muted"># Removes an unassigned shared node.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p><strong>Labels</strong> control service placement. A node with only the <code>web</code> label runs web containers. A node with <code>web,worker</code> runs both. Labels are replaced as a set, so rerun <code>devopsellence node label set</code> with the full list you want the node to keep.</p>
  </section>

  <%# ─── Solo mode ─── %>

  <section class="prose-section" id="solo-mode">
    <h2>Solo mode <span class="mode-badge mode-badge--solo">solo</span></h2>
    <p>Solo mode deploys over SSH without the control plane. The CLI builds the image locally, streams it to each configured node, writes desired state on the node, and the agent reconciles containers from local files.</p>
    <p>Public ingress uses Envoy in solo and shared mode. Add hostnames with <code>devopsellence ingress set</code>; pass <code>--service</code> when the target web service is not already obvious. The agent answers HTTP-01 challenges and keeps HTTPS certificates on the node.</p>

    <h3>Set up a node</h3>
    <p>Use the setup wizard for an existing SSH node or a Hetzner node created by the CLI:</p>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence mode use solo</div>
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence setup</div>
        <div class="tl tl-muted"># Existing node: prompts for host, user, labels, and SSH private key path.</div>
        <div class="tl tl-muted"># Hetzner: prompts for region, size, labels, and defaults to a workspace-scoped generated SSH key.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>The wizard creates <code>devopsellence.yml</code> when needed, records the node and attachment in local solo state, installs Docker when supported, installs <code>devopsellence-agent</code>, starts the <code>devopsellence-agent</code> systemd service, and runs <code>doctor</code>. For provider-created solo nodes it can generate and reuse a workspace-scoped SSH keypair under local state instead of requiring a pre-existing SSH public key path.</p>

    <h3>Create a Hetzner node</h3>
    <p>Provider tokens stay outside the config file. Save a Hetzner token locally, or set <code>DEVOPSELLENCE_HETZNER_API_TOKEN</code> or <code>HCLOUD_TOKEN</code>:</p>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence provider login hetzner</div>
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence node create prod-1 \</div>
        <div class="tl">    --provider hetzner \</div>
        <div class="tl">    --region ash \</div>
        <div class="tl">    --size cpx11</div>
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence node attach prod-1</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>If no default SSH public key exists, <code>node create</code> generates and reuses a workspace-scoped keypair under local state. Pass <code>--ssh-public-key</code> when you want to use a specific key. Provider-managed nodes record non-secret metadata like provider name, server ID, region, size, public host, SSH user, and labels in local solo state at <code>$XDG_STATE_HOME/devopsellence/solo/state.json</code> (default: <code>~/.local/state/devopsellence/solo/state.json</code> when <code>XDG_STATE_HOME</code> is unset). The provider API token and SSH private key value are not written to app config.</p>

    <h3>Solo config</h3>
    <p><code>devopsellence.yml</code> stays workload-only in solo mode. Solo nodes, workspace/environment attachments, and the latest desired environment snapshots live in <code>$XDG_STATE_HOME/devopsellence/solo/state.json</code> (default: <code>~/.local/state/devopsellence/solo/state.json</code> when <code>XDG_STATE_HOME</code> is unset). Generated solo SSH keys stay local under <code>$XDG_STATE_HOME/devopsellence/solo/keys/</code>; SSH private key material is still never written into app config.</p>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
        <span class="terminal-bar-title">devopsellence.yml</span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <pre class="config-pre"><code>schema_version: 6
app:
  type: rails
organization: solo
project: myapp
default_environment: production
build:
  context: .
  dockerfile: Dockerfile
  platforms:
    - linux/amd64
services:
  web:
    kind: web
    ports:
      - name: http
        port: 3000
    healthcheck:
      path: /up
      port: 3000
tasks:
  release:
    service: web
    command: bin/rails db:migrate</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>Labels still control placement in solo mode. Use <code>devopsellence node attach &lt;name&gt;</code> and <code>devopsellence node label set &lt;name&gt; --labels ...</code> to assign environments and placement roles. <code>tasks.release</code> runs once on the first attached node, sorted by node name, that matches its configured service.</p>

    <h3>Deploy and inspect</h3>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence deploy</div>
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence status</div>
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence node logs prod-1</div>
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence doctor</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>Solo deploy scope comes from workspace/environment attachments, not a deploy flag. Use <code>devopsellence node attach &lt;name&gt;</code> and <code>devopsellence node detach &lt;name&gt;</code> to choose which attached nodes receive the rollout.</p>
    <p>During deploy, the CLI shows image transfer phases and compressed bytes sent. Remote Docker access uses plain <code>docker</code> when available and falls back to passwordless <code>sudo</code> for Docker, desired-state writes, status reads, and agent logs.</p>

    <h3>Solo secrets and Rails</h3>
    <p>Solo mode stores deploy secrets in a local <code>.env</code> file next to <code>devopsellence.yml</code>. Do not commit this file.</p>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence secret set DATABASE_URL --value postgres://...</div>
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence secret list</div>
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence secret delete DATABASE_URL</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>For Rails apps, solo deploy automatically injects <code>RAILS_MASTER_KEY</code>. A value in <code>.env</code> wins; otherwise the CLI reads <code>config/master.key</code>. The key is included in desired state sent over SSH and is not written to <code>devopsellence.yml</code>.</p>
    <p>Solo health checks use the same timing defaults as the shared path: interval 5 seconds, timeout 2 seconds, 3 retries, and 1 second start period.</p>
  </section>

  <%# ─── Deploy from terminal ─── %>

  <section class="prose-section" id="deploy-cli">
    <h2>Deploy from terminal</h2>
    <p>The simplest way to deploy. Run <code>devopsellence deploy</code> from your app directory after selecting the workspace mode.</p>

    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence deploy</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>In shared mode, the CLI reads your <code>devopsellence.yml</code>, builds the Docker image, pushes it to the configured registry, publishes a release to the control plane, and waits for nodes to complete the rollout.</p>
    <p>What happens during deploy:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Docker builds your image using the configured Dockerfile.</li>
      <li>The image is pushed to the configured registry. On today's managed backend, that is Google Artifact Registry.</li>
      <li>A signed release is published to the control plane.</li>
      <li>Desired state is published to the configured delivery backend. On today's managed backend, that is GCS.</li>
      <li>If <code>tasks.release</code> is set, it runs on one capable node first.</li>
      <li>Agents pull the new state, pull the image, and start new containers.</li>
      <li>For web services, Envoy proxy shifts traffic to new containers after health checks pass.</li>
      <li>Old containers are stopped and removed.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>Use <code>devopsellence deploy --verbose</code> for detailed output. Use <code>devopsellence status</code> to check the current release state.</p>
  </section>

  <%# ─── Deploy from GitHub Actions ─── %>

  <section class="prose-section" id="deploy-github-actions">
    <h2>Deploy from GitHub Actions <span class="mode-badge mode-badge--shared">shared</span></h2>
    <p>Use the <a href="https://github.com/devopsellence/deploy-action" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">devopsellence/deploy-action</a> to deploy automatically on push.</p>

    <h3>1. Create a deploy token</h3>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence auth token create</div>
        <div class="tl tl-muted"># Creates a long-lived API token for CI use.</div>
        <div class="tl tl-muted"># Save this token — it won't be shown again.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>Add the token as a GitHub secret named <code>DEVOPSELLENCE_TOKEN</code> in your repository settings.</p>

    <h3>2. Add the workflow</h3>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
        <span class="terminal-bar-title">.github/workflows/deploy.yml</span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <pre class="config-pre"><code>name: Deploy
on:
  push:
    branches: [main]

jobs:
  deploy:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
      - uses: devopsellence/deploy-action@v1
        with:
          token: ${{ secrets.DEVOPSELLENCE_TOKEN }}
          organization: acme
          project: myapp
          environment: production</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>3. Set environment variables (optional)</h3>
    <p>Pass runtime environment variables using <code>DEVOPSELLENCE_ENV_VARS</code>. The value is JSON, either flat (applied to all services) or scoped by service name:</p>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
        <span class="terminal-bar-title">.github/workflows/deploy.yml</span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <pre class="config-pre"><code>      - uses: devopsellence/deploy-action@v1
        with:
          token: ${{ secrets.DEVOPSELLENCE_TOKEN }}
          organization: acme
          project: myapp
          environment: production
        env:
          # Flat — applied to all services:
          DEVOPSELLENCE_ENV_VARS: '{"RAILS_ENV":"production"}'

          # Or scoped by service:
          # DEVOPSELLENCE_ENV_VARS: '{"web":{"WEB_CONCURRENCY":"2"},"worker":{"MALLOC_ARENA_MAX":"2"}}'</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>4. Set secrets from CI (optional)</h3>
    <p>Use <code>DEVOPSELLENCE_SECRETS</code> to inject secrets from GitHub Secrets. Same JSON format &mdash; flat or scoped by service:</p>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
        <span class="terminal-bar-title">.github/workflows/deploy.yml</span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <pre class="config-pre"><code>        env:
          DEVOPSELLENCE_SECRETS: |
            {
              "SECRET_KEY_BASE": "${{ secrets.SECRET_KEY_BASE }}",
              "DATABASE_URL": "${{ secrets.DATABASE_URL }}"
            }</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>For a complete working example, see <a href="https://github.com/devopsellence/github-actions-demo-rails" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">devopsellence/github-actions-demo-rails</a>.</p>
  </section>

  <%# ─── Rollback ─── %>

  <section class="prose-section" id="rollback">
    <h2>Rollback</h2>
    <p>There is no special rollback command. Check out the version you want and deploy again:</p>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> git checkout v1.2.3</div>
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence deploy</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%# ─── Configuration reference ─── %>

  <section class="prose-section" id="config-reference">
    <h2>devopsellence.yml</h2>
    <p>The config file lives at the root of your repository. The CLI generates one interactively if it doesn't exist. Here's a full example:</p>

    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
        <span class="terminal-bar-title">devopsellence.yml</span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <pre class="config-pre"><code>schema_version: 6

app:
  type: rails

organization: acme
project: myapp
default_environment: production

build:
  context: .
  dockerfile: Dockerfile

services:
  web:
    kind: web
    command: bundle exec puma -C config/puma.rb
    env:
      RAILS_ENV: production
      RAILS_LOG_TO_STDOUT: "1"
      WEB_CONCURRENCY: "2"
    ports:
      - name: http
        port: 3000
    healthcheck:
      path: /up
      port: 3000
    volumes:
      - source: app_storage
        target: /rails/storage

  worker:
    kind: worker
    command: bundle exec sidekiq
    env:
      RAILS_ENV: production
      MALLOC_ARENA_MAX: "2"
    volumes:
      - source: app_storage
        target: /rails/storage

tasks:
  release:
    service: web
    command: bundle exec rails db:migrate</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>Field reference</h3>
    <dl class="docs-fields">
      <div class="docs-field">
        <dt><code>schema_version</code></dt>
        <dd>Required. Currently <code>5</code>.</dd>
      </div>
      <div class="docs-field">
        <dt><code>app.type</code></dt>
        <dd>Application type. Used for defaults and display. Example: <code>rails</code>.</dd>
      </div>
      <div class="docs-field">
        <dt><code>organization</code></dt>
        <dd>Your organization slug.</dd>
      </div>
      <div class="docs-field">
        <dt><code>project</code></dt>
        <dd>Your project slug.</dd>
      </div>
      <div class="docs-field">
        <dt><code>default_environment</code></dt>
        <dd>Environment used when none is specified. Example: <code>production</code>.</dd>
      </div>
      <div class="docs-field">
        <dt><code>build.context</code></dt>
        <dd>Docker build context path. Usually <code>.</code>.</dd>
      </div>
      <div class="docs-field">
        <dt><code>build.dockerfile</code></dt>
        <dd>Path to Dockerfile relative to context. Default: <code>Dockerfile</code>.</dd>
      </div>
      <div class="docs-field">
        <dt><code>services.*.kind</code></dt>
        <dd>Service runtime kind and placement label. Use <code>web</code>, <code>worker</code>, or <code>accessory</code>. A service runs on nodes whose labels include that kind.</dd>
      </div>
      <div class="docs-field">
        <dt><code>services.*.command</code></dt>
        <dd>The command to start the service process.</dd>
      </div>
      <div class="docs-field">
        <dt><code>services.*.env</code></dt>
        <dd>Key-value environment variables for the service.</dd>
      </div>
      <div class="docs-field">
        <dt><code>services.*.ports</code></dt>
        <dd>Named container ports. Web services must expose an <code>http</code> port.</dd>
      </div>
      <div class="docs-field">
        <dt><code>services.*.healthcheck</code></dt>
        <dd>HTTP path and port for health checks. The agent hits this before shifting traffic.</dd>
      </div>
      <div class="docs-field">
        <dt><code>services.*.volumes</code></dt>
        <dd>Persistent volumes. Each entry has <code>source</code> (volume name) and <code>target</code> (mount path).</dd>
      </div>
      <div class="docs-field">
        <dt><code>tasks.release</code></dt>
        <dd>Runs once on a node matching its configured service before the rollout proceeds. Use for migrations. Failure stops the deploy.</dd>
      </div>
      <div class="docs-field">
        <dt><code>$XDG_STATE_HOME/devopsellence/solo/state.json</code></dt>
        <dd>Solo mode local state. Stores the global node registry, workspace/environment attachments, and the latest desired environment snapshots. Defaults to <code>~/.local/state/devopsellence/solo/state.json</code> when <code>XDG_STATE_HOME</code> is not set.</dd>
      </div>
    </dl>
  </section>

  <%# ─── Secrets ─── %>

  <section class="prose-section" id="secrets">
    <h2>Secrets</h2>
    <p>On today's managed backend, secrets are stored in Google Secret Manager and injected into your containers at runtime. Other backends can use different secret stores. In all cases, the goal is to keep secrets out of your config and deploy logs.</p>

    <h3>Set secrets from the CLI</h3>
    <p>Always use <code>--stdin</code> to avoid secrets in shell history:</p>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> printf '%s' "my-secret-value" | devopsellence secret set SECRET_KEY_BASE --service web --stdin</div>
        <div class="tl">&nbsp;</div>
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence secret list</div>
        <div class="tl tl-muted">web/SECRET_KEY_BASE</div>
        <div class="tl tl-muted">web/DATABASE_URL</div>
        <div class="tl">&nbsp;</div>
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence secret delete SECRET_KEY_BASE --service web</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>Secrets are scoped to a service (<code>web</code> or <code>worker</code>) and automatically exposed to the matching container. No need to reference them in <code>devopsellence.yml</code>.</p>

    <h3>Set secrets from GitHub Actions</h3>
    <p>Use the <code>DEVOPSELLENCE_SECRETS</code> environment variable with JSON. Works both flat and scoped:</p>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
        <span class="terminal-bar-title">.github/workflows/deploy.yml</span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <pre class="config-pre"><code>        env:
          # Flat — same secret in all services:
          DEVOPSELLENCE_SECRETS: |
            {
              "SECRET_KEY_BASE": "${{ secrets.SECRET_KEY_BASE }}"
            }

          # Scoped — different secrets per service:
          DEVOPSELLENCE_SECRETS: |
            {
              "web": {
                "SECRET_KEY_BASE": "${{ secrets.SECRET_KEY_BASE }}",
                "DATABASE_URL": "${{ secrets.DATABASE_URL }}"
              },
              "worker": {
                "DATABASE_URL": "${{ secrets.DATABASE_URL }}"
              }
            }</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <%# ─── Lifecycle hooks ─── %>

  <section class="prose-section" id="lifecycle-hooks">
    <h2>Lifecycle hooks</h2>

    <h3>tasks.release</h3>
    <p><code>tasks.release</code> runs once on a node matching its configured service before the rollout proceeds. It runs in a new container using that service's image, environment variables, secrets, and volume mounts.</p>
    <p>Use it for database migrations or any one-time setup that must succeed before new code goes live. If the command fails (non-zero exit), the deploy stops.</p>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
        <span class="terminal-bar-title">devopsellence.yml</span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <pre class="config-pre"><code>tasks:
  release:
    service: web
    command: bundle exec rails db:migrate</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>Health checks</h3>
    <p>For web services with a <code>healthcheck</code> configured, the agent checks the health endpoint before routing traffic to new containers. This ensures zero-downtime deploys &mdash; old containers keep serving until new ones are healthy.</p>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
        <span class="terminal-bar-title">devopsellence.yml</span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <pre class="config-pre"><code>web:
  healthcheck:
    path: /up
    port: 3000</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>The agent sends HTTP requests to <code>healthcheck.path</code> on <code>healthcheck.port</code>. A 200 response means healthy. The Envoy proxy shifts traffic only after health checks pass.</p>
  </section>

  <%# ─── Ingress ─── %>

  <section class="prose-section" id="ingress">
    <h2>Ingress &amp; HTTPS <span class="mode-badge mode-badge--shared">shared</span></h2>
    <p>Ingress uses the same desired-state shape in solo and shared mode: hostnames, public web nodes, Envoy, and node-owned TLS certificates.</p>

    <h3>Tunnel mode (default)</h3>
    <p>The default for getting started quickly. A Cloudflare tunnel routes traffic from a <code>*.devopsellence.io</code> hostname to a single node. No DNS configuration or open ports required.</p>
    <p>Tunnel mode is great for demos, staging, and home-lab servers that have no public IP &mdash; the tunnel exposes your app publicly without opening ports or configuring a static address. Limitations:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Traffic routes to a <strong>single node</strong> &mdash; no load balancing across multiple servers.</li>
      <li>You get a devopsellence subdomain, not your own domain.</li>
      <li>Not designed for production workloads that need high availability.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Switching to direct DNS (production)</h3>
    <p>Environments start in tunnel mode. When you're ready for production, switch to direct DNS:</p>
    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <div class="tl"><span class="tp">$</span> devopsellence context env ingress --ingress-strategy direct_dns</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>In direct DNS mode, the agent generates its own TLS certificate via Let's Encrypt and terminates HTTPS directly on public web nodes. DNS can point one hostname at more than one node, and one environment can serve more than one hostname.</p>
    <p>To use your own domain:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Create a <strong>CNAME</strong> or <strong>ALIAS</strong> record pointing your domain to the canonical hostname devopsellence assigns to your environment.</li>
      <li>Or, provision a <strong>load balancer</strong> in Cloudflare (or another provider) and point it to your server IPs for multi-node traffic distribution.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>This gives you full control over DNS, load balancing, and failover. Your TLS private key is generated on the server and never leaves it.</p>

    <h3>Choosing a mode</h3>
    <dl class="docs-fields">
      <div class="docs-field">
        <dt><strong>Tunnel</strong></dt>
        <dd>Quick setup, no DNS needed, single node only. Good for demos and staging.</dd>
      </div>
      <div class="docs-field">
        <dt><strong>Direct DNS</strong></dt>
        <dd>Your domain, your load balancer, multi-node support. Use for production.</dd>
      </div>
    </dl>

    <p>Automatic Cloudflare load balancer provisioning in your own zone is coming in an upcoming release.</p>
  </section>

